'''Chiang Peng-chien''' ({{zh-tpw|t=<U+6C5F><U+9D6C><U+5805>|p=Ji<U+0101>ng P<U+00E9>ngji<U+0101>n|w=Chi<U+0101>ng P'<U+00E9>ng-chi<U+0113>n}}; [[April 25]], [[1940]]{{ndash}}[[December 15]], [[2000]]) was the co-founder and first chairperson of the [[Democratic Progressive Party]]. Chiang was elected a member of the [[Legislative Yuan]], the legislative body of the [[Republic of China]] (Taiwan), in 1983 and became a member of the [[Control Yuan]] in 1996.

== Early life ==
Chiang Peng-chien was born [[April 25]], [[1940]], in [[Dadaocheng]], [[Taipei]], [[Taiwan]]. His father was a [[Shoemaking|shoemaker]] from [[Fujian]], [[China]].<ref>{{cite press release|publisher= China.com.cn|url= http://big5.china.com.cn/zhuanti2005/txt/2005-02/05/content_5778171.htm|title= <U+5F9E><U+9774><U+5320><U+4E4B><U+5B50><U+5230><U+6C11><U+9032><U+9EE8><U+5275><U+9EE8><U+4E3B><U+5E2D><U+2014><U+2014><U+7B2C><U+4E00><U+5C46><U+9EE8><U+4E3B><U+5E2D><U+6C5F><U+9D6C><U+5805>|language= [[traditional Chinese]]|date= 2005-02-05|accessdate= 2008-06-16}}</ref>

In 1955, Chiang entered the [[Taipei Municipal Jianguo High School]]. He then got into the [[National Taiwan University]], majoring in [[law]]. After graduation, he passed the [[bar examination]] in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.dpp.org.tw|work= [[Democratic Progressive Party]]|accessdate= 2008-06-16|title= <U+6C11><U+4E3B><U+9032><U+6B65><U+9EE8>}}</ref> Chiang began practicing law after earning his [[Master of Laws|master's degree]].

Chiang advocated for [[human rights]]. He founded the Taiwan Association of Human Rights. On the 1979 [[Human Rights Day]] ([[December 10]]), members of the [[Formosa Magazine]] and other [[Tangwai]] pro-democracy advocates went on a [[Demonstration (people)|demonstration]]. Many of the participants were arrested by the [[Kuomintang|Kuomintang government]] and tried in [[military court]]. Chiang defended [[Lin Yi-hsiung]], one of the "Kaohsiung Eight."<ref name="Death">{{cite press release|url= http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/local/archives/2000/12/16/65714|title= First chairman of DPP dies of pancreatic cancer|date= 2000-12-16|accessdate= 2008-06-21|publisher= [[Taipei Times]]}}</ref>

== Political career ==
Chiang became involved in politics and supported the [[Tangwai movement]]. He was elected a member of the [[Legislative Yuan]] in 1983.<ref name="New Taiwan">{{cite press release|url= http://www.newtaiwan.com.tw/bulletinview.jsp?bulletinid=7636|title= <U+540D><U+58EB><U+98A8><U+683C><U+6C5F><U+9D6C><U+5805><U+3000><U+4E00><U+8EAB><U+50B2><U+9AA8><U+5B64><U+7368><U+884C>|language= [[traditional Chinese]]|publisher= New Taiwan Weekly|date= 2000-12-15|accessdate= 2008-06-22}}</ref> In September 1986, about 130 pro-democracy advocates, including Chiang, gathered at the [[Grand Hotel (Taipei City)|Grand Hotel]] in [[Taipei]] to establish the [[Democratic Progressive Party]] (DPP). On [[November 10]], [[1986]], he was elected the first chairperson of the party.<ref name="New Taiwan"/>

In 1994, Chiang was a candidate for the DPP's nomination in the [[Republic of China municipal elections, 1994|1994 Taipei mayoral election]]. He competed against legislators [[Chen Shui-bian]] and [[Frank Hsieh]] and lost.<ref>{{cite press release|language= [[traditional Chinese]]|url= http://www.libertytimes.com.tw/2006/new/aug/10/today-fo8.htm|title= <U+6C11><U+9032><U+9EE8><U+6B77><U+4EFB><U+9EE8><U+4E3B><U+5E2D> <U+8207><U+6241><U+653F><U+5E9C><U+7684><U+4E92><U+52D5><U+95DC><U+4FC2>|accessdate= 2008-06-22|publisher= [[Liberty Times]]|date= 2006-08-10}}</ref> In 1996, Chiang became a member of the [[Control Yuan]]. He worked to prevent any activities associated with [[Black gold (politics)|black gold]] and actively investigated sensitive cases involved with former political oppression.<ref name="New Taiwan"/>

== Death and legacy ==
Chiang died in December 2000 of [[pancreatic cancer]].<ref name="Death"/> His widow Peng Feng-mei donated his writings and books to the [[Academia Historia]] for display.<ref>{{cite press release|url= http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/local/archives/2001/11/16/111763|title= Museum celebrates contributions of late democracy activist|date= 2001-11-16|accessdate= 2008-06-22|publisher= [[Taipei Times]]}}</ref>

